            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1958-06-24T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1958-06-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="108"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d108">
                <head>108. Memorandum of a Conversation, Department of State, Washington, June 24,
                        1958<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d108fn1">Source: Department of State,
                        Central Files, 689.90D/6–2458. Confidential. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_PLB1">Poullada</persName> on June 25.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" type="conversation-or-meeting-date"
                            when="1958-06-24">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 24, 1958</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Afghan-Pakistan Relations</item>
                </list>
                <p>[Here follows the same list of participants as <ref target="#d106">Document
                        106</ref>.]</p>
                <p>The Prime Minister alluded to Afghanistan’s problems with Pakistan as being one
                    of the reasons which led Afghanistan to accept Soviet aid. With regard to the
                    Pakistan-Afghan transit project, the cooperation and assistance of the United
                    States were greatly appreciated. He wanted to stress, however, that
                    Afghanistan’s political problems with Pakistan still exist, and Afghanistan’s
                    policy has in no way changed as a result of the transit project. Afghanistan
                    desires a peaceful and brotherly solution to its differences with Pakistan, but
                    the Prime Minister emphasized that at this time nothing was being done toward a
                    solution of these political problems.</p>
            </div>
